# Cursor Rules for Vehicle Control Center

## Project Overview
This is a React + TypeScript + Tailwind CSS + Supabase application for vehicle fleet management with approval workflows, notifications (Telegram/LINE), and reporting features.

## Tech Stack
- **Frontend**: React 19, TypeScript, Tailwind CSS 100%
- **Backend**: Supabase (PostgreSQL, Edge Functions, Storage)
- **State Management**: Zustand
- **Charts**: Chart.js + react-chartjs-2
- **Icons**: Lucide React
- **Build Tool**: Vite

## Code Style & Conventions

### TypeScript
- Use TypeScript for all files (`.ts`, `.tsx`)
- Define explicit types for all props, functions, and variables
- Use `Database` types from `types/database.ts` for Supabase types
- Prefer `interface` over `type` for component props
- Use `React.FC<Props>` for functional components

### React Patterns
- Use functional components with hooks only
- Use `useState`, `useEffect`, `useMemo`, `useCallback` appropriately
- Extract custom hooks to `hooks/` directory
- Use `React.memo` for expensive components when needed
- Always handle loading and error states

### File Organization
```
components/
  ui/          # Atomic components (Button, Input, Card, Avatar, etc.)
  layout/      # Layout components (PageLayout, PageHeader)
  [feature]/   # Feature-specific components

views/          # Page-level components
hooks/          # Custom React hooks
services/       # Business logic and API calls
stores/         # Zustand stores
types/          # TypeScript type definitions
utils/          # Utility functions
theme/          # Design tokens
```

### Naming Conventions
- **Components**: PascalCase (`StatusCard.tsx`, `VehicleStatusSection.tsx`)
- **Hooks**: camelCase with `use` prefix (`useAuth.ts`, `useDashboard.ts`)
- **Services**: camelCase (`ticketService.ts`, `vehicleService.ts`)
- **Types/Interfaces**: PascalCase (`TicketWithRelations`, `VehicleStatus`)
- **Files**: Match component/function name exactly

### Import Order
1. React and React-related imports
2. Third-party libraries
3. Internal components
4. Hooks
5. Services
6. Types
7. Utils
8. Styles

Example:
```tsx
import React, { useState, useEffect } from 'react';
import { Truck, Wrench } from 'lucide-react';
import { Button } from '../components/ui/Button';
import { PageLayout } from '../components/layout/PageLayout';
import { useVehicles } from '../hooks';
import { vehicleService } from '../services';
import type { Database } from '../types/database';
```

## Styling Guidelines

### Tailwind CSS (100% Usage)
- **ALWAYS** use Tailwind CSS classes via `className`
- **NEVER** use inline styles (`style={{}}`) except for dynamic values
- **NEVER** create separate CSS files (except `src/index.css` for global styles)
- Use design tokens from `theme/designTokens.ts` as reference

### Design System
- **Colors**: Use custom colors from `tailwind.config.js`:
  - `enterprise-{50|100|500|600|900}` for primary actions
  - `charcoal-{800|900|950}` for dark mode backgrounds
  - `neon-{blue|green|alert}` for accents
  - `slate-{100-900}` for text and borders

- **Spacing**: Use Tailwind spacing scale (`p-4`, `mt-6`, `gap-3`)
- **Typography**: 
  - Page Title: `text-2xl font-bold`
  - Section Title: `text-lg font-semibold`
  - Card Title: `text-base font-medium`
  - Body: `text-sm` or `text-base`

### Z-Index Layers (CRITICAL - Follow Strictly)
Use consistent z-index values to prevent layering issues:
- **z-0**: Base content (default)
- **z-10**: Elevated content (cards, tooltips)
- **z-20**: Sticky headers
- **z-30**: Fixed sidebars
- **z-40**: Overlays, backdrops
- **z-50**: Dropdowns, autocomplete, popovers (⚠️ MUST be higher than cards)
- **z-[60]**: Modals, dialogs
- **z-[70]**: Toasts, notifications
- **z-[100]**: Flyout menus (sidebar submenus)

**Common Patterns:**
```tsx
// ✅ Dropdown/Autocomplete (must be above cards)
<div className="absolute z-50 w-full mt-2 bg-white dark:bg-slate-800 ...">

// ✅ Modal backdrop
<div className="fixed inset-0 z-40 bg-black/50">

// ✅ Modal content
<div className="fixed inset-0 z-[60] flex items-center justify-center">

// ✅ Flyout submenu
<div className="fixed z-[100] ...">

// ❌ Wrong - Dropdown too low
<div className="absolute z-10 ..."> {/* Will go behind cards */}
```

**Stacking Context Issue:**
Components with `backdrop-blur`, `opacity`, or `transform` create NEW stacking contexts.
Child z-index cannot escape parent's stacking context!

```tsx
// ❌ Wrong: z-50 on dropdown won't work
<Card> {/* Has backdrop-blur, creates stacking context at z-0 */}
  <div className="absolute z-50"> {/* Can't go above other Cards! */}
  
// ✅ Correct: Add z-index to Card itself when dropdown is open
<Card className={`${hasDropdown ? 'relative z-50' : ''}`}>
  <div className="absolute z-50"> {/* Now works! */}
```

### Dark Mode
- **ALWAYS** support dark mode using `dark:` prefix
- Test both light and dark modes
- Use `dark:bg-charcoal-900` for dark backgrounds
- Use `dark:text-white` for dark text

### Responsive Design
- Use Tailwind responsive breakpoints: `sm:`, `md:`, `lg:`, `xl:`
- Mobile-first approach
- Test on multiple screen sizes

### Component Styling
```tsx
// ✅ Good: Use Tailwind classes with dark mode
<div className="p-6 bg-white dark:bg-slate-800 rounded-xl border border-slate-200 dark:border-slate-600">
  <h2 className="text-2xl font-bold text-slate-900 dark:text-white">Title</h2>
</div>

// ❌ Bad: Inline styles
<div style={{ padding: '24px', backgroundColor: 'white' }}>
```

### Input Fields & Forms (MUST Follow)
**ALWAYS** include these dark mode classes for inputs:
```tsx
// ✅ Text Input
<input
  className="w-full px-3 py-2 
    border border-gray-300 dark:border-slate-600 
    rounded-lg 
    bg-white dark:bg-slate-800 
    text-gray-900 dark:text-white 
    placeholder-gray-400 dark:placeholder-gray-500 
    focus:ring-2 focus:ring-blue-500 dark:focus:ring-blue-400
    disabled:opacity-50 disabled:cursor-not-allowed"
/>

// ✅ Textarea
<textarea
  className="w-full px-3 py-2 
    border border-gray-300 dark:border-slate-600 
    rounded-lg 
    bg-white dark:bg-slate-800 
    text-gray-900 dark:text-white 
    placeholder-gray-400 dark:placeholder-gray-500"
/>

// ✅ Select/Dropdown Results
<div className="absolute z-50 w-full mt-2 
  bg-white dark:bg-slate-800 
  border border-gray-200 dark:border-slate-600 
  rounded-xl 
  shadow-lg dark:shadow-black/50">
  <button className="w-full p-4 text-left 
    hover:bg-gray-50 dark:hover:bg-slate-700/50 
    border-b border-gray-100 dark:border-slate-700">
    <p className="text-gray-900 dark:text-white">Item</p>
    <p className="text-gray-500 dark:text-gray-400">Detail</p>
  </button>
</div>

// ❌ Wrong: Missing dark mode classes
<input className="border rounded px-3 py-2" />
```

### Number Inputs Best Practices
**CRITICAL**: Prevent auto-fill and unwanted default values:
```tsx
// ✅ Correct: Allow empty state, no default values
const [quantity, setQuantity] = useState<string | number>(''); // Start empty

<input
  type="number"
  value={quantity === '' ? '' : quantity}
  onChange={(e) => setQuantity(e.target.value)} // Keep as string
  placeholder="จำนวน"
  min="0"
  className="..."
/>

// When calculating, convert to number
const total = (Number(quantity) || 0) * price;

// When submitting, validate
if (Number(quantity) <= 0) {
  alert('กรุณาใส่จำนวนที่มากกว่า 0');
  return;
}

// ❌ Wrong: Default value causes issues
const [quantity, setQuantity] = useState(1); // Auto-fills with 1
onChange={(e) => setQuantity(parseInt(e.target.value) || 1)} // Can't clear
```

### Dropdown/Autocomplete Click Outside Handler
**ALWAYS** implement click-outside to close dropdowns:
```tsx
import React, { useRef, useEffect } from 'react';

// 1. Create ref for dropdown container
const dropdownRef = useRef<HTMLDivElement>(null);

// 2. Add click outside handler
useEffect(() => {
  const handleClickOutside = (event: MouseEvent) => {
    if (dropdownRef.current && !dropdownRef.current.contains(event.target as Node)) {
      // Close dropdown
      setShowDropdown(false);
      // or clear search: setSearch('');
    }
  };

  document.addEventListener('mousedown', handleClickOutside);
  return () => {
    document.removeEventListener('mousedown', handleClickOutside);
  };
}, [showDropdown]); // Add dependencies

// 3. Attach ref to container (not just dropdown!)
<div className="relative" ref={dropdownRef}>
  <input ... />
  {showDropdown && (
    <div className="absolute z-50 ...">
      {/* Dropdown content */}
    </div>
  )}
</div>

// ❌ Wrong: Ref on dropdown only
<div className="relative">
  <input ... />
  <div ref={dropdownRef} className="absolute z-50 ..."> {/* Wrong! */}
```

## Component Guidelines

### Reusable Components
- **ALWAYS** use components from `components/ui/` when available:
  - `Button` (variants: primary, secondary, outline, danger)
  - `Card`, `CardHeader`, `CardContent`
  - `Input` (with label and error support)
  - `Avatar`
  - `Skeleton` (for loading states)
  - `ConfirmDialog`

- **ALWAYS** use `PageLayout` for all page-level components
- **NEVER** create duplicate components that already exist

### Component Structure
```tsx
// 1. Imports
import React from 'react';
import { Button } from '../components/ui/Button';

// 2. Types/Interfaces
interface MyComponentProps {
  title: string;
  onAction?: () => void;
}

// 3. Component
export const MyComponent: React.FC<MyComponentProps> = ({
  title,
  onAction,
}) => {
  // 4. Hooks
  const [state, setState] = useState();
  
  // 5. Handlers
  const handleClick = () => {
    // ...
  };
  
  // 6. Render
  return (
    <div className="...">
      {/* ... */}
    </div>
  );
};
```

## Supabase Guidelines

### Database Types
- **ALWAYS** use types from `types/database.ts`
- Use Supabase generated types: `Database['public']['Tables']['vehicles']['Row']`
- Use view types: `Database['public']['Views']['vehicle_dashboard']['Row']`

### RLS (Row Level Security)
- **ALWAYS** respect RLS policies
- Test with different user roles (admin, manager, inspector, driver)
- Use service role key only in Edge Functions, never in frontend

### Edge Functions
- Located in `supabase/functions/`
- Use TypeScript
- Handle errors gracefully
- Log important events for debugging

### Storage
- Use `storageService.ts` for file uploads
- Organize files: `pending-pdfs/`, `signed-tickets/`, `vehicle-images/`
- Always handle upload progress and errors

## State Management

### Zustand Stores
- Use Zustand for global state (`stores/`)
- Keep stores focused and small
- Use `create` from Zustand

### Local State
- Use `useState` for component-local state
- Use `useMemo` for expensive computations
- Use `useCallback` for functions passed to child components

### Server State
- Use custom hooks (`useVehicles`, `useTickets`, etc.) for server state
- Always handle loading and error states
- Use caching when appropriate

## Error Handling

### API Calls
- **ALWAYS** handle errors in try-catch blocks
- Show user-friendly error messages
- Log errors for debugging
- Provide retry mechanisms when appropriate

### Form Validation
- Validate on submit
- Show inline error messages
- Use `Input` component's `error` prop

### Loading States
- Show loading indicators during async operations
- Use `Skeleton` component for content loading
- Never show blank screens during loading

## Testing & Quality

### Code Quality
- Write clean, readable code
- Add comments for complex logic
- Remove console.logs before committing (except for debugging)
- Use meaningful variable and function names

### Performance
- Use `React.memo` for expensive components
- Use `useMemo` for expensive calculations
- Use `useCallback` for event handlers passed to children
- Lazy load heavy components when possible

## Documentation

### Comments
- Add JSDoc comments for complex functions
- Explain "why" not "what" in comments
- Keep comments up-to-date with code changes

### File Headers
- Add descriptive file headers for complex files:
```tsx
// Ticket Detail View - Show detailed information about a ticket with approval workflow
```

## Git & Version Control

### Branch Naming
- `feature/` for new features
- `fix/` for bug fixes
- `refactor/` for refactoring
- `docs/` for documentation

### Commit Messages
- Use clear, descriptive commit messages
- Reference issue numbers when applicable
- Use present tense ("Add feature" not "Added feature")

## Common Patterns

### Data Fetching
```tsx
const { data, loading, error, refetch } = useVehicles();

if (loading) return <Skeleton />;
if (error) return <ErrorState onRetry={refetch} />;
if (!data || data.length === 0) return <EmptyState />;

return <DataDisplay data={data} />;
```

### Form Handling
```tsx
const [formData, setFormData] = useState({ name: '', email: '' });
const [errors, setErrors] = useState<Record<string, string>>({});

const handleSubmit = async (e: React.FormEvent) => {
  e.preventDefault();
  // Validation
  // Submit
};
```

### Conditional Rendering
```tsx
// ✅ Good: Clear and readable
{isLoading ? (
  <Skeleton />
) : hasError ? (
  <ErrorState />
) : (
  <Content />
)}

// ❌ Bad: Nested ternaries
{isLoading ? <Skeleton /> : hasError ? <ErrorState /> : <Content />}
```

## Thai Language Support

### Text Content
- All user-facing text should be in Thai
- Use proper Thai typography
- Keep technical terms in English when appropriate (e.g., "PDF", "API")

### Date/Time Formatting
- Use Thai locale: `toLocaleDateString('th-TH')`
- Format: "วัน เดือน ปี" or "DD/MM/YYYY"

## Security

### Environment Variables
- **NEVER** commit `.env.local` or `.env` files
- Use `VITE_` prefix for Vite environment variables
- Store sensitive keys in Supabase Edge Functions only

### User Input
- **ALWAYS** validate and sanitize user input
- Use parameterized queries for database operations
- Respect RLS policies

## When Creating New Features

1. **Check existing components** - Don't duplicate functionality
2. **Follow file structure** - Put files in correct directories
3. **Use design tokens** - Don't hardcode colors/spacing
4. **Support dark mode** - Always add dark mode styles
5. **Handle errors** - Always handle loading and error states
6. **Test thoroughly** - Test with different user roles
7. **Update documentation** - Update relevant docs if needed

## Code Review Checklist

Before submitting code:
- [ ] TypeScript types are correct
- [ ] No console.logs (except for debugging)
- [ ] Dark mode is supported
- [ ] Responsive design works
- [ ] Error handling is implemented
- [ ] Loading states are handled
- [ ] Uses existing components when possible
- [ ] Follows naming conventions
- [ ] Imports are organized correctly
- [ ] Code is readable and well-commented

